I trade indices with a very short time frame. I invest in stocks with an intermediate time frame. For me the two can coexist - there is no uniform strategy for all as it depends on timeframe and risk appetite.
I dont short naked puts. Seen too many disasters with this strategy. Many of my floor trading friends went out of biz in Oct. 1987 effecting this strategy.
I and others look forward to reading it.

It seems to me, given the extraordinary volatility that "the current trend" is next to impossible to gauge With VIX here there is a randomness to price as we have seen. Up 1000, down 1000. The way I counter that and make trades is to play the projected range and gauge reward/risk

A projected trading range (based on my own input) S&P 2850-3300 is the way I roll. Not sure if I am specifically predicting where mkt will be a month from now - only the range. This is my guidance to trading. The lower we go the more reward and vice versa.

arguing (for most traders and investors) to maintain a continued higher than usual amount of cash reserves. * The 65 handle overnight drop in futures take the S&P Index back to a test of the 3050 support
